tspan.tspan: When I was a babby ram, people would make
me so angry and I would try to ram them. "You can't do that" they would say, "that is
antisocial behaviour. That's not how society can function". But it worked. I would ram them and
they would run away. But they would come back again the next day. "Don't do this. We should help each
other - that's how a community works". I'd ram them again. They'd run away again. They'd keep me protected
while I tended the grounds and the sheep. The warmth of my wool kept me happy through the nights. I felt like I
owned it all - doubtless, everybody else felt the same. There was this time: before the other ram; and there was that
time: after the other ram. Temperatures had risen. My wool grew over my eyes. It was so fucking hot. I looked over the
ewes (I needed someone to distract me) and found a set of horns, not my own. I was fascinated and a change of 'scenery'
was exactly what I needed. I trotted on over and put on my
signature style to show that I was
ready for it and get them in the mood too: I grunted at the
ram, nudged him a bit, grunted
again. Maybe it was just my obscured vision, but he didn't
seem to give much attention. A
common ewe would have taken pity on me by now, or been
annoyed enough to get it over
with... Well I didn't mind a bit of a chase. I nudged
again and pawed at his legs for
a while. Fuck, the heat was getting to me - maybe all my
wool wasn't his vibe. It was
when I was pretty tired and about to give up that he
finally reciprocated and turned
around. I was getting ready to fall into my
distraction from the heat and
the wool, but there were intermittent sharp
sounds nearby - and getting
closer. I felt a nipping at my leg.
Maybe teeth? I kicked away at it
with my hind leg and tried to ignore
it. Again! It bit me again. And that
incessant barking. I lugged myself
around and tried to find the culprit

text.tspan: through the winding rings of the wool in my eyes. Clearly there was a cunt that

tspan.tspan: needed a ramming again, and not my good
kind. But
it moved so fast, like a little
black blur - I couldn't ram what ran
around me in
circles - I was helpless. As
quickly as the blur had come it had left
at the call of the
people I would often ram away
from me. I reorientated myself, shaking
my head to clear
my vision of the wool. The other
ram was over the other side of the field
now. Was that
all that was about? I thought.
Whatever, I guess, I'm just as happy with
a ewe - though
it shouldn't have been a problem
for anyone else anyhow. Not long after, the hound was
sent after me again. I swear

text.tspan: the fucker enjoys it, bounding about with legs made of springs. My mobility is for

tspan.tspan: shit with all the wool bounding my sight and
gait, but the dog doesn't
consider this. Just keeps nipping at my legs
if I
go too slow or off of some
course the people controlling him are
leading us on. They took me

text.tspan: inside some tin structure, a floor of concrete. My mind was putting pieces

tspan.tspan: together: another ram, a new guard
dog, some
shed I've never been to
before. The completed puzzle
wasn't looking good.
Before I could act on the
thought, a loud click

text.tspan: and a heavy buzzing accompanied a force that pulled
me off my hooves and onto my back. They brought the

tspan.tspan: strange buzzing device down to
my neck
as I
shrieked: You

text.tspan: don't have to replace me; I'll stop ramming
you, I'll go where the dog tells me to go, I won't
try to fuck a ram ever again, only ewes
from now on. The buzzing pushed up against
me and my wool fell over my face. They stripped
me to skin and forced me into a small, metal pen
enclosure. I was cold and alone that morning. I used
to like the cold when I had what I needed to endure it.

tspan.tspan: I rammed my head
against the thin tin shed wall.

text.tspan: Each hit thinking of how much they needed to control me for

make. How they are probably why my
wool grows over my
eyes and that I cannot shed it
myself. They've
forced me to be dependent on
them, but
they're dependent on me too.
